thoughts.content:
To ensure the hero image fills the section while maintaining aspect ratio, I propose this snippet:

```css
.hero {
  position: relative;
  overflow: hidden;
}

.hero-media {
  position: absolute;
  inset: 0;
}

.hero .hero-media img {
  width: 100%;
  height: 100%;
  object-fit: cover;
  object-position: center;
}
```

Make sure to remove the inline styles or override with `!important`. For cropping, `object-fit: cover` is used, and dynamic cropping can be adjusted via `object-position`.

parts:
Use `object-fit: cover` and make the `<img>` stretch to the hero’s box. In your case the inline `style="height:auto"` on the `<img>` will prevent that, so override it (or remove it).

Add this to your CSS:

```css
/* Make the hero image always fill the hero’s height */
.hero {
  position: relative;   /* already present; needed for absolute positioning */
  overflow: hidden;     /* hide the crop */
}

/* Pin the <picture> to the hero’s edges so it defines the backdrop */
.hero-media {
  position: absolute;
  inset: 0;             /* top:0 right:0 bottom:0 left:0 */
  z-index: 1;           /* stays behind the text (hero-content has z-index:2) */
  height: 100%;
  pointer-events: none; /* image never blocks clicks on CTAs */
}

/* Force the <img> to fill the box and crop as needed */
.hero .hero-media img {
  width: 100%;
  height: 100% !important;  /* override inline height:auto */
  object-fit: cover;         /* fill + maintain aspect ratio, crop overflow */
  object-position: center;   /* adjust focal point as needed */
}
```

Notes
- This works whether the hero ends up taller or shorter than the image’s intrinsic size. The image will always fill the hero’s height; excess width/height is cropped.
- If you need to bias the crop (e.g., keep a face higher in frame), tweak `object-position` (e.g., `50% 35%`).
- If you ever prefer letterboxing instead of cropping, change `object-fit: cover` → `contain` (the image will then fit entirely and may leave empty space).
